SIMPLE: inconsistency
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inconsistency
<hw>In`con*sist"en*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Inconsistencies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[Cf. F. <ets>inconsistance</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being inconsistent;
discordance in respect to sentiment or action; such contrariety between
two things that both can not exist or be true together; disagreement;
incompatibility.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a perfect <qex>inconsistency</qex> between that which is
of debt and that which is of free gift.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Absurdity in argument ore narration; incoherence or
irreconcilability in the parts of a statement, argument, or narration;
that which is inconsistent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If a man would register all his opinions upon love, politics,
religion, and learning, what a bundle of <qex>inconsistencies</qex> and
contradictions would appear at last!</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Lack of stability or uniformity; unsteadiness;
changeableness; variableness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mutability of temper, and <qex>inconsistency</qex> with ourselves,
is the greatest weakness of human nature.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inconsistent</ent>⟦br⟧
